ith the target package. Oh, and does CGLIB naming policy automatically generate in the same package as the superclass?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating implementation issues**\\n\\nI'm noticing a potential issue here: if the generated class implements an interface with a method named \\\"format,\\\" but the target method is called \\\"compose,\\\" this could get tricky. The generated implementation named \\\"format\\\" is calling \\\"compose.\\\" Good to have an assert to prove the mapping is correct. I also need to remember to add a license header and write a new file. Hmm, maybe a user-code-filter should be checked as well?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_8Um0MPMZ5SzFxp5fZzQBSdsB|fc_0e44fffe3272007f0169f59a6f013081a0b9231076c7a71285", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-core/5.3.15/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 261, "output": 1348, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30793, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777703511974, "responseId": "resp_0e44fffe3272007f0169f59a58697881a09d9c8c9e6545e0f7"}}
